10.44.
 [20 marks] We substitute 
\begin_inset Formula \( y(x)=e^{\lambda x} \)
\end_inset 

 in the corresponding homogeneous differential equation (setting the RHS
 to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula \( y''=2y'+y=0 \)
\end_inset 

).
 The characteristic equation is 
\begin_inset Formula \( \lambda ^{2}-2\lambda +1 \)
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula \( (\lambda -1)^{2} \)
\end_inset 

, hence the solution to the homogeneous problem is 
\begin_inset Formula \( y(x)=c_{1}e^{x}+c_{2}xe^{x} \)
\end_inset 

.
 The inhomogeneous term is a polynomial, hence we guess a polynomial solution
 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \( ax^{2}+bx+c \)
\end_inset 

.
 Substituting and collecting the terms we get 
\begin_inset Formula \( a=1 \)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( b=4 \)
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \( c=5 \)
\end_inset 

.
 Hence the general solution is 
\begin_inset Formula \( y(x)=c_{1}e^{x}+c_{2}xe^{x}+x^{2}+4x+5 \)
\end_inset 

.
 
