10.49.
 [20 marks] We substitute 
\begin_inset Formula \( y(x)=e^{\lambda x} \)
\end_inset 

 in the corresponding homogeneous differential equation (setting the RHS
 to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula \( y'-y \)
\end_inset 

).
 The characteristic equation is 
\begin_inset Formula \( \lambda -1 \)
\end_inset 

, hence the solution to the homogeneous problem is 
\begin_inset Formula \( y(x)=c_{1}e^{x} \)
\end_inset 

.
 The inhomogeneous term is an exponential, hence we guess an exponential
 solution of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \( e^{x} \)
\end_inset 

.
 This first guess will fail since this is also the solution to the homogeneous
 problem.
 Therefore, we modifiy our guess by multiplying it by 
\begin_inset Formula \( x \)
\end_inset 

.
 We try 
\begin_inset Formula \( Axe^{x} \)
\end_inset 

, substituting we get 
\begin_inset Formula \( Ae^{x}+Axe^{x}-Axe^{x}=e^{x} \)
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula \( Ae^{x}=e^{x} \)
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula \( A=1 \)
\end_inset 

.
 Hence the general solution is 
\begin_inset Formula \( y=c_{1}e^{x}+xe^{x} \)
\end_inset 

.
